<font color="#FF0000">CONCERNING FLAGS</font><br>
<tt>Tue Apr 29  1:32:30 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Doc Spatz, A question about the flags:<br>
     Is the denial of flying another country's flag at a special event the norm in Orange County or that community? Here in Philadelphia Irish flags sprout all over the place on St. Patrick's Day. There's also Polish flags on Pulaski Day, German flags on Von Steuben Day, Mexican flags on Cinco de Mayo and God knows what else I'm forgetting.<br><br>
     You ought to try my neighborhood. Within 2 blocks of my home are a Portuguese Pastelaria, an Italian pastry shop, a Vietnamese grocery, an Asian grocery run by ethnic Chinese from Vietnam, a Spanish language newspaper, a Korean owned pharmacy, an Austrian/Irish owned funeral parlor, a black owned catering business and hall.  My parish has Masses in English, Spanish, Portuguese, Malayalam and Hmong.  The Mormon missionary pairs in the area have nametags in two languages, English and either Spanish, Vietnamese or Cambodian. A &quot;white bread&quot; existence is possible here, but you would have to go through some contortions to maintain it. 
<p><code>-- gerald_ney@icpphil.navy.com  (Gerald Ney, &quot;professor&quot;, 7/68-7/69) </code><p>


